 Fix a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 that is reflexive and transitive.
 Then define a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 as such.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the objects of 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 is a set containing the element 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(a,b)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By reflexivity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom(a,a)$
\end_inset

 is always nonempty because it contains the element 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{a}=(a,a)$
\end_inset

 always.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:b\to c$
\end_inset

 are any two morphisms then this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim c$
\end_inset

.
 By transitivity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim c$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $gf:A\to C$
\end_inset

 is a well defined morphism.
 In fact it is the element 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c).$
\end_inset

 That is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom(a,c)=\{gf\}=\{(a,c)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b,g:b\to c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h:c\to d$
\end_inset

 are morphisms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $hg=(b,d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $gf=(a,c)$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $(hg)f=(a,d)=h(gf)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 for any morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{b}f=(a,b)=f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f1_{a}=(a,b)=f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting fact about this category is that given any morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

,
 take any object 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and a pair of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha',\alpha'':c\to a$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $c,\alpha',\alpha''$
\end_inset

 are so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\alpha'=f\alpha''
\]

\end_inset

 then this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'=\alpha''$
\end_inset

.
 In fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'=\alpha''$
\end_inset

 is always true because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(c,a)$
\end_inset

 is always a singleton or empty.
 This discussion elucidates the fact that every morphism in this category is a 
\emph on
monomorphism
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact,
 take any morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

 and fix any object 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

.
 Take any pair of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta',\beta'':b\to c$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'f=\beta''f$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'=\beta''$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'=\beta''$
\end_inset

 always holds for the same reason as above.
 Also,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'f=\beta''f$
\end_inset

 also always holds because 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'f=(b,c)$
\end_inset

 and so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta''f$
\end_inset

.
 Every morphism in this category is an 
\emph on
epimorphism.
\end_layout

