\begin_layout Standard
We learned about the slice category,
 now let us see an example of a category that is dual to this - the coslice category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Eg-3.8"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 For a concrete example,
 take the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\Obj(\mathsf{Set)}$
\end_inset

 is the class of all sets.
 Fix a singleton 
\begin_inset Formula $\{*\}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 we define a new category 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}^{*}$
\end_inset

 whose objects are all the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\{*\}\to A$
\end_inset

 for any object 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}.$
\end_inset

 Any object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

 may be identified as a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,s)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s=f(*)$
\end_inset

 because the information of any object in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}^{*}$
\end_inset

 comprises of the choice of the nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and of an element 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset

 to in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A morphism between two objects 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(T,t)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}^{*}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma:S\to T$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
such that 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(s)=t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Objects in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}^{*}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\emph on
pointed sets
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-3.1"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 be a category.
 Consider a structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\Obj(\catC^{\mathsf{op}})\coloneqq\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for a pair of objects 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\Obj(\catC^{\mathsf{op}})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,B)\coloneqq\Hom_{\catC}(B,A)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that is,
 given any pair of objects 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 of the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

,
 arrows from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are arrows from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Take any pair of objects 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\Obj(\catC^{\mathsf{op}})$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}\colon\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,B)\times\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(B,C)\to\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,C)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
by the following rule:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f\coloneqq f\ocircle g
\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ocircle$
\end_inset

 in the right hand side is the composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(A,A)$
\end_inset

 is nonempty for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

 and objects of 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

 are simply objects in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,A)$
\end_inset

 is also nonempty and contains the same 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{A}\in\Hom_{\catC}(A,A)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}g$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,C)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(C,A)$
\end_inset

.
 The well definedness of the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}$
\end_inset

follows immediately from the well definedness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ocircle$
\end_inset

.
 Just take elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f,f'\in\Hom_{\catC}(B,A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g,g'\in\Hom_{\catC}(C,B)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f=f'$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g'$
\end_inset

 and then notice that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f= & f\ocircle g\\
= & f'\ocircle g'\\
= & g'\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f'
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next,
 take the morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B,g:B\to C,h:C\to D$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC^{\mathsf{op}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(h\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}g)\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f & =f\ocircle(g\ocircle h)\\
 & =(f\ocircle g)\ocircle h\\
 & =h\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}\big(g\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f\bigr)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
showing that the composition is associative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 pick a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,B)$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1_{B}\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}f= & f\ocircle1_{B}\\
= & fp
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\ocircle_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}1_{A}= & 1_{A}\ocircle f\\
= & f
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This completes our construction and proof of construction of the opposite category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
We choose to indicate the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Hom_{\catC^{\mathsf{op}}}(A,B)$
\end_inset

 by just the same symbol when we consider it in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(B,A)$
\end_inset

.
 This might not be a bit tricky to deal with initially but it does make writing the proof quite more convenient.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-3.2"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a finite set,
 how large is 
\begin_inset Formula $\End_{\mathsf{Set}}(A)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
The morphisms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

 are simply functions between the objects (sets) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

.
 So we are simply counting the number of functions from a finite set to itself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
I claim that for a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements,
 there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{n}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to A$
\end_inset

.
 Since bijections compose to give bijections,
 it suffices to prove the statement for a set of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
We notice that there is a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\dots,n\}^{\{1,\dots,n\}}\to\prod^{n}_{k=1}\{1,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\mapsto(f(i))^{n}_{i=1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
is the obvious candidate.
 By the product rule of combinatorics,
 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod^{n}_{k=1}\{1,\dots,n\}$
\end_inset

 has cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{n}$
\end_inset

 and we are done.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

