\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-3.10"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Since the objects of a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 are not necessarily sets,
 it is not clear how to make sense of a notion of 'subobjects' in general.
 In some situations,
 it does make sense to talk about subobjects,
 and the subobjects of any given object A in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $A\to\Omega$
\end_inset

 for a fixed,
 special object 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

,
 called a subobject classifier.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}$
\end_inset

 has a subobject classifier.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\coloneqq\{0,1\}\in\Obj(\mathsf{Set})$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly every subobject of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Obj(\mathsf{Set})$
\end_inset

 should be its subset and every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be identified by its indicator 
\begin_inset Formula $B\to\Omega,b\mapsto1$
\end_inset

 if element 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 satisifes 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mapsto0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 The set of subobjects of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 should be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\powerset(A)$
\end_inset

 so we will establish a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\powerset(A)\to\{0,1\}^{A}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
This bijection will be given by the map 
\begin_inset Formula $B\mapsto\one_{B}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\one_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the indicator of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 This map is injective because 
\begin_inset Formula $\one_{C}=\one_{B}$
\end_inset

 says an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

.
 So,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C=B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
For surjectivity,
 suppose we are given a map 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\{0,1\}^{A}$
\end_inset

.
 We will find a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(B)=g$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $B\coloneqq g^{-1}(1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(B)=\one_{B}.$
\end_inset

 If we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\one_{B}=g$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 then we are done.
 So,
 take any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in B$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\one_{B}(a)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)=1$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in g^{-1}(1)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A\setminus B$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\one_{B}(a)=0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)=0$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $a\notin g^{-1}(1)$
\end_inset

 and every point of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must map under 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to either 0 or 1.
 Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\one_{B}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(B)=\one_{B}=g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 is a subobject classifier for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Set}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If in a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 we equip it by the equality relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim\coloneqq=$
\end_inset

 then the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 whose objects are 
\begin_inset Formula $\Obj(\catC)=S$
\end_inset

 and morphisms are simply identities 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,a)$
\end_inset

 for every object 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in S$
\end_inset

 (all the morphisms are identities because no 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 for distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

).
 This is a catetgory in which every morphism is an isomorphism because theyre all identity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-4.1"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Suppose we are given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 different morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}\circ f_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 is always well defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,\dots,n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 any valid expression involving parenthesis 
\begin_inset Formula $($
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $)$
\end_inset

,
 elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1,}\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

 and the composition operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 is always independent of the placement of the parenthesis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}$
\end_inset

 a well formed expression of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 By this we mean that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 composition operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 and an arbitrary number of appropriately nested parenthesis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
It suffices to show that any 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be equivalently written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ f_{3})\circ f_{4})\circ\dots)\circ f_{k-1})\circ f_{k}$
\end_inset

 which allows us to speak of the unique legal expression involving 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{k}$
\end_inset

 and we can simply write that as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\circ f_{2}\circ\dots\circ f_{k}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
We proceed by strong induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
For the base case of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}\circ(f_{2}\circ f_{3})=(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ f_{3}$
\end_inset

 is simply the associativity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Our induction hypothesis is that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{k}=(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ f_{3})\circ f_{4})\circ\dots)\circ f_{n-1})\circ f_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{k}$
\end_inset

 of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\bZ_{>0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $3\leq k\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 have length 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 there are 
\begin_inset Formula $l,m\in\bZ_{>0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $l+m=n+1$
\end_inset

 and expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{n+1}=K_{l}\circ K_{m}.$
\end_inset

 Now,
 there are two cases:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Case 1:
 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $l=n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{m}=f_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 So,
 by the induction hypothesis 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{l}=(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ\dots)\circ f_{n-1})\circ f_{n}
\]

\end_inset

 Consequently,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{n+1}=(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ\dots)\circ f_{n-1})\circ f_{n})\circ f_{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Case 2:
 m > 1.
 By the induction hypothesis,
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{m}$
\end_inset

 can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{m}=K_{m-1}\circ f_{n+1}$
\end_inset

,
 and so 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{n+1}=K_{l}\circ(K_{m-1}\circ f_{n+1})=(K_{l}\circ K_{m-1})\circ f_{n+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
But,
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{l}\circ K_{m-1}$
\end_inset

 is itself an expression of length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 so,
 by the induction hypothesis,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{l}\circ K_{m-1}=(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ f_{3})\circ\dots)\circ f_{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Finally,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{n+1}=(\dots(f_{1}\circ f_{2})\circ f_{3})\circ\dots)\circ f_{n})\circ f_{n+1}
\]

\end_inset

 which completes the induction step.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-4.2"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
 define the category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 as such:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Obj(\catC)=S$
\end_inset

 and given objects 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in S,$
\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 then there is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $a\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}b\in\Hom_{\catC}(a,b)$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(a,b)=\{(a,b)\}$
\end_inset

 and if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 are not related by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC}(a,b)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 For what conditions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 a groupoid?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
We claim that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation then 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 is a groupoid.
 Indeed,
 we saw that 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 is a category if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive and transitive.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is also symmetric,
 that is,
 if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in S,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a\sim b$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $b\sim a$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed in this case,
 every morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

 has the left inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $g:b\to a$
\end_inset

 given as 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $(b,a)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
so that 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $gf=(b,a)(a,b)=(a,a)=1_{a}.$
\end_inset

 
\series default
Similarly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:a\to b$
\end_inset

 has the right inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $g=(b,a)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)(b,a)=(b,b)=1_{b}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "Ex-4.3"
key "aluffi"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 be objects of a category 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Hom_{\catC}(A,B)$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a right inverse,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an epimorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Find an epimorphism without a right inverse.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Suppose a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

 between objects 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

 has a right inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $g:B\to A$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg=1_{B}.$
\end_inset

 Then,
 Fix an object 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and a pair of morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha',\alpha'':B\to Z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\circ f=\alpha''\circ f$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\circ f\circ g=\alpha''\circ f\circ g$
\end_inset

 which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\circ1_{B}=\alpha''\circ1_{B}$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'=\alpha''$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
Just take the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)$
\end_inset

 in the category given in Eg-3.3.
 Any right inverse should make it so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,3)\circ g=(3,3)$
\end_inset

 so only 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,2)$
\end_inset

 is a choice but this is not a morphism that makes sense in this category.
\begin_inset Formula $\hfill\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
