 Can you define a subcategory 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC_{\text{nonmono}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 by restricting to morphisms that are 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
monomorphisms?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC$
\end_inset

 is the category in Eg-3.3 then every morphism is 
\emph on
monic.

\emph default
 In that case the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC_{\text{nonmono}}}(a,a)$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\Obj(\catC)$
\end_inset

 is always empty because even 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{A}$
\end_inset

 is monic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution*
It might be worth thinking about whether we can do this if we do admit 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{A}$
\end_inset

 to every 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hom_{\catC_{\text{nonmono}}}(a,a)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\catC_{\text{nonmono}}$
\end_inset

.
 Perhaps we might have to look at some examples like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{Grp}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{CRing}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

